column11: The question will be suspended on 31 August 2022 and the outcome determined using the latest data as reported by Our World in Data for the "People fully vaccinated" metric, relative to population, as displayed here at approximately 5:00PM ET on 2 September 2022: https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations?country=ZAF. For example, South Africa's share of the population fully vaccinated against COVID-19 as of 1 December 2021 was 24.25%. If the named sourced changes the way it presents the data, we will make the appropriate modifications to the resolution instructions.

column6: At this point with 24 hours to go, only 32.17% have been fully vaccinated
As per many other forecasters, there seems to be a plateau and now we're at the end of the question's forecast period.
Politicians prattle on. A few people still wear masks though they are no longer mandated but we have consigned COVID to history. The vaccination rate will not change.

Maybe I should have used the @ thing.... Was a tricky one with all the ppl that did not go back for seconds, but not too unusual, has happened in a lot of other countries, the UK also has just under 5% that did not go back and the USA is about 12%
Its Africa
Barring any accounting errors this now looks like it will close even lower than the 32.8% forecast back in June.
Same forecast range and rationale as from June 29th but with four weeks less scope for the situation to deviate: 32.8-33.4% total
No Worries.
Staying around 32%, I doubt they can get another 3% in the next month.

Waited untill the latest figures are out, they are again not updating over the weekend, which looks like it will be the trend from now on, most likely due to numbers drying up considerably. As of 19 July totally vaccinated figures stand at 32.23% -- Vaccinated numbers stand at 37.21% -- From 01 May to now a static figure of approximately 5% has been present which is believed to be a Non Returning Cluster. This could be a group of people that have not returned for their second dose of a two part vaccination

Just checked this source here. Looks like the curve is starting to stagnate at at around 32-33%. Will be a close call to 35%. Still 7 weeks to go, if they make it above 35% it will be marginal. At the moment I don't thing they reach 35%. Definitely not my last forecast on that question.
All in on Bucket one: Figures of fully vaccinated as of 5 July stood at 31.78 - As per previous posts there is a cluster of ppl that have not gone back for the second jab

I suppose a lot can change over two months, but with vaccination rates still low after the recent declines it seems that the trend would be towards 0.5%/month for complete courses, closing at 32.8-33.4%, unless some new factor affects the context such as a new variant or big outbreak. Both are possible, but even so I'd then expect the first doses to be prioritised (they are still below 40%).

As of 25 June it stands at 31.7% fully vaccinated and we appear to be on target for reaching 32% by 8 July. It took 46 days to increase by one percentage point (01 May to 15 June) and as indicated also on target for going up half a percentage point in half the days, ie 23 days. This would mean that it would then have to increase three percentage points in 56 days
On the back of excellent analysis by others.
As per previous rationales, particularly from May 27th https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1457860

I calculated the average daily increase of share of people with a complete initial protocol for the last i) 121 days, ii) 61 days and iii) 37 days. The daily percentage increase were 0.026%, 0.021% and 0.020%. The pace is slowing down - since only 73 days are left before the deadline, I reckon the value on September 1st will be between 33.0% and 33.5%.
Many thanks to @Eliac @SE_Meyer and @paulm for the thoughtful analysis and discussion below.

01 May fully vaccinated figures stood at 30.55% 46 days later it increased by 1% to 31.55 (15 June) It is strongly suspected that there is a cluster of people that have only had one dose of a two dose vaccine and are not going back for the second dose, this group in my opinion is estimated to be about 4 - 5% in size
Confirming my prediction

@paulm @SE_Meyer I do not think it will get over 35% -- Here's why. 01 May total Vax figures stood at 30.55% as of 01 June they are only 31.28% not even up by one percentage. They have just coming out of their 5th wave and vax figures did go up a bit as part of the 5th wave drive, there might be another push for numbers as they head into the Southern Hemisphere winter, but they would need to get beyond 1.1% each month to get close to that target
Still looks like a closing result of 33.4-34.8% to me, I'm not sure why the crowd is so strongly expecting 35-50% ??
Not enough motivation anymore

The recent rise in cases has lead to the vaccination rate increasing, but first doses have only just cleared 35.8% and second doses are still 5% behind. A 50% increase in uptake is needed over the term to reach 35+ which looks achievable but still not very likely given the context and prior data. It could well get very close though - I’d estimate 34.2-35.4%.

This is going to be close, bear in mind that a good portion of the 4.5% of ppl not fully vaccinated are made up of individuals that had one shot of a two dose vaccine and have not gone back and will most likely never go back for the second dose, so while it looks a slam dunk that it will go over the 35% mark by the end of August, it may not because of the large number that have not had the second shot. Having said that, there now seems to be a 5th wave going on and vax numbers are picking up again as they head into Winter, but numbers could fizzle out again just as quickly. It was 30.55 on the first of May and 30.84 on the 13th of May. At the current rate of vaccinations, it could be just under or just over 35% - - also not sure if the round up factor might come into play and 34.6 gets counted as 35%
Only 30.27 are currently vaccinated and the data is stagnant. I have been over confident with my trends I think
https://www.gna.org.gh/1.21449607

In 4 months the number has increased only 5%, and not at all in the last 2 months. While I am guessing data collection is not good and there will probably be a big jump at some point, if you take 5% over 4 months as an average pace, over the next 5 months I would expect it to increase less rather than more. Covid is not a problem there.

Would advise ppl to put some 'less than 35%' into their mix of forecasting, while they are nearly up to 34% on jabs, it would appear a lot of ppl have not gone back for their second jab and will not count as fully vaccinated

There are new, locally produced vaccines, new rules, new promotions but reported vaccinations remain stubbornly low. A glimmer of change happened in the most recent data where a big jump was added to the tally pointing towards new numbers coming in from somewhere - probably better accounting rather than more people. While current rates are unlikely to exceed 50% in the timeline there I enough risk around data collection and jumps in number like that recently reported to keep my forecast low.

Just a heads up to everyone, it would appear that there is a number of ppl that have only had one shot of Pfizer and have not gone back for the second shot, so will not count as fully vaccinated. While you you see that the vaccination rate is heading towards 35% it may not translate into Fully Vaccinated because of the number not going back for their second jab
I think the impetus for vaccine rollout is going to fizzle as restrictions drop across the world. I predict that the curve, that was raising so well, is going to flatten and wane.

Currently at 29%, which means they have increased approximately 5% in 2 months. At this same rate they would increase 15 more percent by September which would be 44%. But I would expect the rate of vaccination to decline.
Large spike upwards in shots recently as well as this: https://news.un.org/en/story/2022/02/1111972
Take-up is slow.
Now at 27%
Data today shows that 27.9 % of the population in South Africa is fully vaccinated. If numbers continue that way, it may be possible to reach 35-50% of the population.

Quite a slowdown over December and January. Partly would have been the Omicron effect. Keep away from public if possible, partly Christmas, partly middle of hot summer. All just theories... Big jump to Bin2 for my forecast

South Africans are tired of COVID 19. We have eased restrictions. The curfew has been lifted. Masks are still required and every public place religiously practices the ritualised hand sanitation thing. But nobody gives a sh*t anymore. Certainly, nobody is standing in a queue to get vaccinated.

SA is tracking at 32% today... I believe they'll get higher by September. I do worry that they lose momentum with the announcement that they are loosening the covid controls and restrictions that have been in place for the last 2 years. The psychological impact may be that residents interpreted the loosening of controls as "it's over" and feel they do not need to show up for the jab. Bad for my score and bad for the country.

26.8% currently fully vaccinated. Given Omicron's quick run in South Africa and not resulting in a relatively severe impact, it is not likely that people will see an urgency to seek vaccination in massive numbers if they have not already done so --unless situation changes. But they have had supply and delivery issues in addition to public skepticism about vaccines. The government doesn't seem likely to impose a vaccinate mandate right now. Pres. Ramaphosa had said he'd call for a task team to advice on a mandate but that was when Omicron was first hitting. (https://theconversation.com/vaccine-mandates-in-south-africa-where-are-they-most-needed-173253) Ramaphosa himself is fully vaccinated and just finished isolation after testing positive on Dec 20, having mild symptoms. He has been a strong critic of wealthy nations "hoarding vaccines" “Of around 6 billion doses administered worldwide, only 2% of these have been administered in Africa, which has a population of 1.2 billion,” he said in an address to the Global Covid-19 Summit. “This must be unjust and it is also immoral.” https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-09-23/south-africa-s-ramaphosa-says-rich-nations-are-vaccine-hoarding

There is a marked slowdown in SA vaccination in December, it went from 24.3% on Dec 1 to 26.4% on Jan 1. And this is during the peak of Omikron wave, so it is hard to imagine vaccination rate increasing after that. I feel that 35% is going to be pretty tough to get to, but of course there is a lot of time and anything can happen. Also, I find it strange that growd forecast shows bin 1 at 0% while recent activity clearly indicates quite a few forecasts that have non-zero numbers. Am I missing something here?
This really depends what is meant by "fully vaccinated".

The population of South Africa has substantial immunity to virus presently and vaccine uptake has slowed. It has averaged 1% per week increase since July 2021 largely due to vaccine supply. Deaths and cases even with omicron have not accelerated.

By going through the other rationales and my gut feeling, more than 50% is quite realistic. By September 2022 I see the number between 60 and 70%. I base my assumption and the government is able to procure enough vaccines for well over 80% and everybody, who wants to get the jab will have it by then. I guess a general widespread suspicion will keep number of people between the aforementioned 60% and 70%. What also could play a role might be HIV imune compromised people who can't get it, but as I understand, the access to retroviral medication is nowadays much more reliable than it used to be let's say 10 to 15 years ago. So that might be factor but I have no clue big or small.
Just throwing in a junk forecast because the question should have included the definition of "fully vaccinated" and I had to look up the webpage referenced to infer that fully meant more than one.

If the country can obtain enough vaccine for everyone who wants it, I would say they could achieve 80% vaccinated but given the shortage of vaccine and the unlikely ability of the country to obtain more than they’re already getting, it’s going to be tough to vaccinate more than 45-50% of their people. Another factor would be if Moderna would release the vaccine recipe and allow South Africa to make it themselves. That would be another way to achieve higher vaccination rates.

the vaccination strategy is aggressive and if it has the 'legs' it will reach most people in the next year. however, South Africa is pathologically inefficient - the success so far might be results that should be attributed to the private sector, once it needs to spill over into mostly government servicing the poorer population, the success might dwindle.

Despite it having a more affluent status than much of the rest of sub-saharan Africa, apartheid-era mistrust of the government is evident. Currently, approximately 25% of the population of South Africa is fully-vaccinated. Over the next several months, into early 2022, that number will continue to climb toward 50%. However, I expect that number to stall out between 45 and 50 percent, as there are just too many South Africans who are vehemently opposed to government efforts to vaccinate its citizens.

If you think about the richness snd the poorness in the country, you really can’t make a certain forecast. If you put in the urban and rural factors, and the remnants of apartheid still alive today, it could go any way.
The supply side looks ready.
Its Africa
It is going to be near 50% give or take a few points the lesson from the scare of Omicron will acelerate some vaccination numbers.

1) According to Google's Our World Data the current full vaccination rate in South Africa is 24.6% with the trend line still rising still slowly rising. 2) According to the South African government (https://www.gov.za/covid-19/vaccine/strategy) their roll out is phased with healthy, low-risk over 18yo's which comprise some 22M people being the last to be vaccinated. 3) While they are clearly falling short of the 67% goal by end of 2021 its seems likely they will get to 35%+ by end of 2022. 4) Given SA gov. historic positions on pandemics and vaccines (AIDS etc) and an underfunded public health system it seems likely that vaccination rates will plateau with a relatively large part of the population being vax sceptics. 5) Wildcard: Omni variant spurs world to increase donations of vaccine to SA and scares population into getting the jab.
Africa has about 1/8 the fatalities per capita of the United States from covid. I don't think this is a major concern for them.
